<subSubSection pageId="15" pageNumber="80" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1437,152,863]" pageId="15" pageNumber="80">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,801,827]" pageId="15" pageNumber="80">Remarks.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Heller H. E. Andrewes" authorityYear="1903" box="[323,602,800,826]" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Pheropsophus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="80" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="prophylax">
<emphasis box="[323,602,800,826]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="80">Pheropsophus prophylax</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is quite similar to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Chaudoir" authorityYear="1876" box="[814,959,800,826]" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Pheropsophus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="80" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aptinoides">
<emphasis box="[814,959,800,826]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="80">P. aptinoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from which it differs by black head; long, narrow pronotum. It is endemic to the Indo-Burma hotspot of biodiversity.
</paragraph>
